<DOC><DOCNO> AP890327-0158 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 2022EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Peru 1stLd-Writethru a0645 03-27 0370</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0645,0379</SECOND><HEAD>Rebels Blamed For Runaway Railroad Car That Killed Three</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to include runaway rail car, police deaths.Pick up 5th graf pvs, `The nation's...'</HEAD><DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leftist guerrillas released an empty railroadcar parked at a siding Monday, and the car killed three people asit rumbled down the tracks for nine miles before coming to a halt,officials reported.   Enafer, the state railroad company, said the car was set loosenear Chosica, 25 miles east of Lima. It blamed left-wing rebels butdid not name a specific group.   The brief statement did not identify the three people who werekilled or give any other details.   Officials reported two policemen were slain by gunmen of theMaoist Shining Path movement in separate attacks.   They said a police captain was fatally wounded by fourguerrillas who shot him as he walking to his home in Huancayo, 140miles east of Lima, Sunday night. The other policeman was slainSunday night in a downtown market in Pucallpa, 235 miles northeastof Lima, according to the officials.   Peruvians began receiving their mail Monday when postal serviceresumed after a strike for nearly two months by members of theNational Federation of Postal Workers who sought salary increases.   The government and union reached an agreement Thursday on a wageand benefit package but no details were released.   About 85 percent of Peru's 7,000 postal employees participatedin the strike that began Feb. 2 and halted home mail delivery andother services.   Officials said some 10 million letters were placed in postoffice storerooms during the strike.   The nation's 70,000 miners stayed on the job after the NationalFederation of Mine Workers called off a three-day strike set tobegin Monday.   The union said talks with the government were planned Tuesdayand the strike could be rescheduled depending on the outcome of themeeting. Miners were demanding that contracts be negotiated jointlyinstead of on the current company-by-company basis.   Peru has been hit with dozens of strikes since the economyspiraled into deep recession a year ago.   In most cases, workers demanded pay increases to offsetinflation, which hit 1,722 percent in 1988.</TEXT></DOC>